Due to the possibility of strong rains, flooding, and high winds, school will not be in session tomorrow. School will resume on Monday the 31st for all students. Anyone who has not attended this week for orientation will be provided their information and given help when school resumes Monday. Sorry for the inconvenience; however, student and staff safety is our number one priority when dealing with mother nature. Stay safe and we can't wait to see our students on Monday.

Virtual student’s technology and information will not be dispersed this week. We will make an announcement soon on the day and time for the disbursement of that information.

The schedule for the first week is listed below. We have split the alphabet into 4 even groups. We will be following this schedule during the week of August 24th ONLY. On August 31st, we will resume classes Monday- Thursday.

Monday 8/24- A through C
Tuesday 8/25- D through J
Wednesday 8/26- K through R
Thursday 8/27- S through Z

If your household has students with different last names then they will all come on the day of the oldest child's name.

The buses will run during the first week like normal.

We will be posting information and dates soon for our virtual students to receive their log in information and technology. The pick up time will be during the week of August 24th.

post_text: Beginning on Wednesday, June 10th, Haworth will begin the Summer Feeding Program. It will continue until July 16. We will be offering to go meals at the School Cafeteria. We will not have a dine in option. All meals will be picked up in a drive through format like we did in March, April and May. The meals may be picked up between 10:00 and 11:00 am. We will be offering meals at the School Cafeteria only. The students do not have to be in the vehicle at the time of pick up; however, you will have to provide the names of the students. Any child 18 or under is eligible to receive meals.

post_text:
Oklahoma’s Promise: ALERT for 10th-Grade Parents with Recent Income Loss

https://www.okhighered.org/okpromise/

If your student is or was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma’s Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income. The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020 deadline at

https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/Oklahoma_Promise/apply.html?application_id=3544

You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu.

post_text:
Parents & Community,

Haworth Graduation Ceremony Update

The current weather forecast is predicting weather that will hinder our outdoor graduation plans. Therefore, we will be postponing our ceremony until June 6th-2:00 PM.
If the State’s Phase 3 plans are in place and we are allowed to have an indoor graduation we will do so in the auditorium. If guidelines will not allow us to do so, and we cannot meet in a large indoor group setting, we will change the graduation to outside and hold the same ceremony that would be held inside. We will provide that information as soon as possible.
We know this is not an ideal situation; however, we are dealing with unprecedented times and providing our seniors with a safe ceremony to recognize them for their years of hard work. More information will be provided soon as we work through this situation. Thank you for your patience.

Go Lions!

Professionally,

Jason Price
Haworth Superintendent

Parents & Community,

As distance learning continues to move forward and ongoing adjustments are made, I would like to thank you for your support and encouragement that many of you have given to our administration and staff during this time. It has been without a doubt an interesting time in education and in every other area of life. During this time of adjustment it is good to know that we have the support and understanding of many who are concerned and are willing to pull together. Once again, we will continue to keep you informed and work for the good of our students as this scenario plays out. Thank you for your support and determination to continue to work together.

Go Lions!

Jason Price
Superintendent

During this time of adjustment it is good to know that we have the support and understanding of many who are concerned and are willing to pull together. Once again, we will continue to keep you informed and work for the good of our students as this scenario plays out. Thank you for your support and determination to continue to work together.

Go Lions!

Jason Price
Superintendent

Parent & Community,

The State Board of Education met today in Oklahoma City and determined that all schools will be out for the remainder of the current school year. This also includes all extra curricular activities.

Currently, our meal program will continue into the first weeks of May. A specific cut off date will be provided at a later time.

Even though school is out, there will be distance learning required for us to participate in. This will begin Monday, April 6th. Our staff will begin the process of putting this area together. We will provide you further details of how this will work as quickly as possible.

Once again, we don’t have all the answers but as we learn more we will inform you. It is one step at a time. Continue to be safe and work together.

We will provide further information concerning upcoming academic requirements and other areas as the overall plan is organized.

Go Lions!

Superintendent
Jason Price

post_text:
Parents, Community, & Staff,

Although we are in interesting times in education it has been a privilege to watch staff, board members, community members, and businesses come together and continue to meet the challenges we face each day. First and foremost, the well-being of our students is our #1 priority. Today, while handing out meals at Haworth, Goodwater, and Tom many children received food because of the willingness of a caring group of people to serve. It can’t be done alone and for those who have served I say “thank you!” Keep it up!

As for school itself, there are many questions that do not have answers yet as we continue to work with the Oklahoma State State Department of Education. As we receive answers we will pass them on to you as quickly as possible. Our goal is to do what is right and serve our students as well as possible as we are allowed. Continue to stay safe and work together. We will get through this!

Go Lions!

Superintendent
Jason Price

post_text: Congratulations to Samual Mendez on being selected as Kiwanis Student of the Month!
shared_text:
Idabel Kiwanis
February 11 at 9:20 PM ·

Two excellent young men were honored as Students of the Month at the Kiwanis meeting today. First President Frank Acker recognized Idabel High School senior Andy He. Andy is a great student who attends KTC part time and is involved in SkillsUSA. He is interested in several areas of science including biology, chemistry, and computer science. His hobbies are photography and cooking and working out.
The next photo shows Samuel Mendez (center) receiving the certificate attesting to his status as Student of the Month from Haworth High School by VP Bruce Short, accompanied by Haworth principal Brent Smith, who lauded Samuel’s volunteer spirit. Samuel is also attending KTC part-time, where he studies industrial technology. Samuel has played basketball but is now planning to run track and medals in archery. He plans to attend Southeastern to earn a degree in occupational safety.

post_text:
Haworth Community,

Today we discovered a threatening message inside of our high school that caused us to evacuate the school. Although we are uncertain if it was a legitimate threat, we always hold the safety of our students and staff at the highest importance. After being notified we cleared the school and ran our buses as soon as possible. It was done in a quality manner. After the buildings were cleared with an outstanding effort from our staff, the Sheriff Department entered the facilities and performed a manual sweep of the area. Nothing was discovered. However, evidence was taken and information will be evaluated. As always, if information is received that we discover who is responsible, the highest level of action will be taken. School is a place for learning and we want to keep Haworth at the highest level possible. I hope you will continue to do your part in supporting our school as we continue to raise our standards. Thank you for your support and dedication to Haworth Public School.

Professionally,

Jason Price-Superintendent
text:
Haworth Community,

Today we discovered a threatening message inside of our high school that caused us to evacuate the school. Although we are uncertain if it was a legitimate threat, we always hold the safety of our students and staff at the highest importance. After being notified we cleared the school and ran our buses as soon as possible. It was done in a quality manner. After the buildings were cleared with an outstanding effort from our staff, the Sheriff Department entered the facilities and performed a manual sweep of the area. Nothing was discovered. However, evidence was taken and information will be evaluated. As always, if information is received that we discover who is responsible, the highest level of action will be taken. School is a place for learning and we want to keep Haworth at the highest level possible. I hope you will continue to do your part in supporting our school as we continue to raise our standards. Thank you for your support and dedication to Haworth Public School.

Professionally,

Jason Price-Superintendent

It's that time of year!!! We are in need of your help in adopting Angels(students) for Christmas! Our Angels’ cards are at the Haworth Country Store and Kates Quick Stop, ready to be Adopted for Christmas; we really appreciate these businesses help! Our Haworth Community is the BEST and always pulls through in helping Adopt our Angels in need, and we have many that are in need this year. Please go and find the Angels that you would be willing to Adopt this Christmas season. Those that Adopt these Angels are Angels themselves. We have the Angels up early for those that want to take advantage of early Christmas 🎄 sales. Please write your name and contact number next to the Angel’s card number on the adoption check-out sheets by the registers. Ask for help if you don’t know the adoption process. Thank-you in advance for being a blessing to these students and their families!!! Happy Thanksgiving and MERRY CHRISTMAS 🎄🎁 😇

10th and 11th grade US history students have an opportunity, if they drive, to travel to the Idabel Public Library to attend a lecture over WWI presented by Master Storyteller John Hinkle from 4 to 5 pm tomorrow, September 27th.

Students MUST have written permission from a parent/guardian in order to leave school early.

Mr. Boyd will be at the Idabel Public library at 3:45pm. Students must check in with Mr. Boyd to be considered excused from their last hour class.

Students who are able to attend this event will receive extra credit in their US history course. For exceptions, students will need to see Mr. Boyd.
